A comparison between Skanect, Reconstructme and Kscan3D software, using a Rev1 Kinect sensor for xbox360...

Skanect lost, its uninstalled. Main reason= $140 if you want more than 5000 polygons.
The UI is cookie cutter at best, but functions quite well, and super simple to use.

ReconstructMe, had some awesome videos and a great sales pitch. it seems to do alright and its free. the 3Dselfie seems like a cool feature and i plan on trying it out in the future... for my comparison, the capture was finicky. it kept losing tracking and was super slow to recover. but produced a decent model with a high polygon count.

Kscan3d.. Well ok then.. after i dealt with getting it installed and working... stupid .net crap... its pretty awesome.... I ran a Batch capture of 20 images using Mesh alignment and it was super simple, count down tone and shutter sound queues you to rotate the object and get out of the scene... aligning and combining meshes was pretty fun and fluid. the export process worried as i thought it hung up, but it was exporting a 53mb .stl file after all...

STL files are named accordingly, hopefully... loading them into thingview will allow you to inspect them closer with out downloading... im pretty sure these are not fit for printing, so print at your own risk ;)

title: Diamond head to Anet A-8 mounting Bracket

description.text:
This is a mounting system for a 3 color ,diamond head , to an A-net A-8 .
It fits directly to the Anet Aluminum Linear bearings , with no modifications , using the file labeled, 4 mm holes . Another file is also available with 3mm holes , which is design to specifically fit our Micrometer height Adjuster , which is shown in the photos.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2185918

The mount uses a flange plate between the Diamond Fan & extruder shroud , as the original mounting flange is particularly awkward to use , as its on the same plane as the linear bearing mounts , which makes screw access impossible.

The shroud came with my hotend , but if you dont have it you can download it here
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:720520

The flange design also allows for a quick release system for head removal. M3 studs are used , ( make them by cutting the heads off 40mm x M3 screws)
The bracket is counter bored to allow the nuts to recess into the bracket & wing nuts are used to hold the assembly together , complete with the cooling fan . Spinning off the 4 wing nuts will allow the whole head & fan to be removed .
Look carefully at all photos to see how to assemble & mount everything .

At this stage i haven't upgraded the motherboard with additional stepper drivers. I'm only using the different colors on different prints , so im just swapping the stepper plug to the color i want , in order to test everything at present.

Currently investigating a new board , like the rhumba ,
or seeing of i can add some stepper driver board to the Anet motherboard.

Please comment if you have already done these mods , & add some photos if you make one & find it useful .

Remixed from an excellent design by Thingiverse user and certified amateur radio operator Loren Butler (V01PWF), the intent of this project was to make a set of 3D printable iambic paddles that were as portable as possible, while still comfortable enough to use at a desk. This is the mini version, designed to use 6-32 screws but as compact as possible. Unlike the previous two designs, all screws will need to be cut to the correct length detailed below. The narrow version of this key can be found here, and the base mountable version here.

Hardware Used:

  • 2x 6-32 x 1 inch phillips flat pan head screws trimmed to 18mm thread length for paddle pivots
  • 1x 6-32 x 1 inch phillips flat pan head screw trimmed to 21mm thread length for the ground contact/cover
  • 2x 6-32 phillips flat pan head screws trimmed to 11.5mm thread length for paddle contacts
  • 2x 6-32 nuts/springs and washers for paddle contact screws
  • Optional 2x 6-32 1/4 inch phillips flat pan head screws for attaching the cover
  • Optional 3x #6 ring terminals for joining wires to the paddle and ground contact screws
  • 1x 1/8 inch stereo jack or hot glue
  • 1x Spring from a retractable pen (3.5mm outer diametre, 10mm length), or 2x neodymium magnets
  • 3x short lengths of stranded wire

The paddles use a spring from an empty retractable ball point pen, and are tension adjustable via a set of pockets along the inside of each arm. A suggestion from wz2prich is to use neodymium magnes glued to the arms instead of a spring. Arm travel to contact is adjustable but the resting point is fixed.If you want the paddle travel to be adjustable while the cover is in place, use springs in place of the nuts on the paddle contact screws. The plug at the rear of the paddles is a 1/8" stereo jack which could lead to an electronic keyer, radio, or pc interface. A tip from Thingiverse user KD9AYE is to glue the wires in place, eliminating the need for a stereo jack. Photos of his build of the narrow and base mountable versions of these paddles can be found here. The cover is held in place by the ground contact screw. Two optional screws at the rear of the case can also be used to hold the cover in place, but are not necessary.

description.text:
I've been working on this 3D printed frame with 4mm Carbon Fibre arms for over a year now.

The arms are off the shelf and only cost £11 delivered to the UK which I believe is a worth while investment since all the 3D printed quads I have tried suffer from weak arms that constantly break.

After my first flight and crash tests it's stood up to all I could throw at it, very interesting actually. Flight characteristics are spot on with free fall being straight due to perfect balancing of parts.

One thing I did notice is that the VTX signal is much better without all that carbon around. Even this dipole antenna allowed good reception around my tree line. All my carbon builds suffer almost lost signal at the far points of the course, not so with this!

I am now on version 3 and I feel it is complete because it is almost indestructible. I know, its a massive claim and I guess if it was crashing into walls and concrete all day then OK I think it would break. But for field flying, crashing into gates and flag poles this is just fine.

In the next few weeks I'll do some build video's on my YouTube channel "TheBionicBone" <-- No Spaces :). I will try to include everything including the basic set up of the flight controller and, if you follow exactly using the same parts then it should be possible to share a settings file.

description.text:
Print the bracket, and cover in the direction they appear in the .STL files. Closed end of bracket towards the print bed. I printed mine in 0.1mm layer heights but 0.2mm should be more than enough.

Since the Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus/Monoprice Maker Select Plus are 24V native printers you need to make sure you wire the LED panels in SERIES so that each panel will only get 12V of power.

The light panels I used are these: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00H9OQKCM/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

If you purchase those from Amazon you will recieve the two 6 SMD LED panels from Amazon, a little soldering is involved to rewire the backs of the LED panels like shown in the pictures. I wired the light directly in line with the fan for the heatsink on the hotend which is constantly running when the printer is switched on. It is up to you if you want to wire it directly to the fan, or you can put an inline plug on the light like I did. The lights from Amazon come with a bunch of connectors, I just reused those.

The side cover is VERY TIGHT. Lightly scrape away at the edges to give it a tight fit into the bracket. Too tight and you will break the little tab where the wires run, too loose and it will fall out while printing. So keep test fitting and DO NOT force it in there.

This is my custom super heavy duty wall mount for electric longboards and skateboards. Larger longboards seem to be 25lbs or less. If you really want to hang by the truck you could probably just scale this down but I have not tried it.

Proteção e estética

Proteção contra choques.

description.text:
I wanted to use my Hitachi or Dremel to trim down micro quad propellers as it seemed to get a better round profile for use on a ducted frame. This jig has 2 main parts:

  • Inner motor mount (sub-jig) snuggly centers and fits an 8.5mm motor (more inner jigs to come for different motors). Has captures one end for 3mm nuts. I liked this idea better than using drill big/needle/nail because it snugly fits and gives you the same movement as you would get on the quad itself. This sub assembly slides in the grooves of the outer jig to adjust length of shortened blade. Slightly <3mm holes are provided on the side to thread 3mm bolts from outer jig to secure inner jig.

  • Outer jig threads on to standard Dremel/Hitachi and provides a 14mm opening all the way to the top. For me i use a straight carbide cutting bit that fits no problem, but wider (such as abrasive cylinders) can be inserted after the jig is threaded on to the tool. Slots on either side accommodate a 3mmx8-10mm bolt to secure inner jig from movement once positioned.

Overall i've had great success with this little tool, so hopefully it helps someone else out too :) Cheers!

title: Huxley feet filament holder quick release mod

description.text:
This is a modification to the Huxley feet filament holder by AndrewCraigie.
It allows you to quickly and easily remove the filament holder from the frame without messing around with nuts and washers (if like me you have fitted extra nuts to keep things in place) so you can more easily load new filament.
Refitting is quick and easy and the filament holder is retained securely with a printed face plate and wing nuts.

You will need: 2 x Quick release vertices 2 x Quick release clips 2 x M8 Wing Nuts 1 x AndrewCraigies Huxley feet filament holder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21955 The quick release vertices replace the two top vertices of the frame. The existing spindle (the M8 threaded bar) should just drop into the new ones. The clips fit over the ends of the spindle and the lugs locate into the holes in the vertices. Secure with M8 wing nuts and you are done! There 3 stl files, one with both the clip and the vertex for your printing convenience. The others are the parts on their own. I was worried that the new vertex wouldn't be very strong. I printed them in PLA at 20% in fill, 3 sold layers, 2 perimiters and they seem plenty strong enough to me. Note: I'm not sure how this should be licensed as I suspect the vertex is a derivative of the reprap Huxley vertex which would make it GPL, but the filament holder is CC. Eitherway, I will leave it default at CC unless someone tells me otherwise. Enjoy!

(This was my very first piece that I've designed and I've learned from its many design flaws, but I am including it because it does work and is useful.)

Do not just download and print. The .SCAD file will need to be modified based upon the key of the instrument and the tolerance of the printer.

The base drone on my Scottish Smallpipes snapped. At that point in time the company that made my pipes was changing hands and I could not order a replacement piece.

This is my reconstruction of the missing piece based upon careful measurements of the original.

All of the measurements in the system are based upon my printer and tolerances. You may need to change numbers to get things to work for you.

When using PLA I could print this item as one piece.

When using ABS, I had to break into the separate pieces. I could not keep the drone body from falling over.

Cleaning

If printed as several pieces, carefully clean out the bottom of the main body before inserting the base.

Insert the brass tubing

I used hobby store brass tubing to line the inside of the drone. This gave a much smoother bore than could be gotten through printing.

This is also tradition, as brass lining drones has been done on the Great Highlands for hundreds of years.

Assemble

If printed as separate pieces, clean the bottom of the main body as best as you can before attaching the reed seat.

Note that the reed seat as a tapered end. This goes on the outside.

Hot glue holds the pieces together quite well.

Trimming

Because I could no get the reed seat and the main body to come together as well as I had expected, I trimmed the length of the drone down slightly to compensate.

If printed as one piece, this should not be needed.

I designed this piece by taking very careful measurements of the original broken drone pieces and cross-checking them against every online source I could find.

Note that the fireside pipes come in several different keys. These length measurements are for the Bb version of the pipes. If trying to replace the drone for a set keyed in A, length measurements will need to be tweaked slightly.

description.text:
Video files are uploaded with the source files. This is a claw designed to grab objects of varying sizes. The grabbing arms are always parallel to each other, so any size object with flat sides can be picked up.
Its powered by an HS-311 servo running on an Arduino Uno. I made this claw to learn about robotics and servos. I find the relationship between the gears and free arms that make the grabbing arms parallel interesting. There is an attachment point on the side of claw for another HS-311 servo. This allows the claw to be attached onto some other system.

The parts were all cut out of 3mm acrylic from a Epilog Mini 18 Laser. Some of the arms are weak and should be larger than I designed. My claw has eight grabbing arms (four for each side) and two free arms. All other parts only need to be made once.
The two different gears are important, having two of the same gear will not allow the grabbing arms to be parallel. The spacers were printed on a Makerbot Replicator. There needs to be three of each size. The vertical mount is attached to both other mounts by acrylic glue. The glue also hold together each set of grabbing arms. Hockey tape is wrapped around the grabbing arms to increase friction and allow the claw to grab heavier objects.

title: Wheel Hub Cover for Worx 803 Beast Truck Wheel

description.text: This is a replacement for the center wheel hub cover on a Worx 803 Beast Truck wheel.

Printer:

Reach 3D Printer

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

40%

Notes:

The original caps were relatively thin plastic, and after a few broke and fell off, we decided that we could 3D Print a better one.

The Ultra Wheel Company website indicates that these wheels are compatible with F-150's, Toyota Tacomas and Jeep Wranglers.
http://www.ultrawheel.com/wheel/2615/803-beast-truck/

The cap's bolt holes are spaced at 150 mm across. This wheel only requires two bolts to hold the cap on, but we modeled usable holes at all 8 locations in case one or two locations crack or break. I found that the printed hubs where coming out a little small on my printer, so I scaled them up by about 1.5%, and that made them almost dead-on accurate. If you're interested in printing this, I recommend printing a center section across two opposing bolt holes, and check-fit it against your wheel.

The first four caps are currently mounted on a 2007 Chevy Silverado 2500 HD. 20" wheels, using an 8X165 bolt pattern (8 bolts, 165mm/6.5" pattern diameter)

Our intention is to primer or clear-coat the caps eventually, we don't have any experience with PLA parts being splashed with mud or water over and over. ABS might be a little more environmentally stable, but for now we're just going to see what these look like after a few months. We've mused about the possibility of gluing in steel inserts at the bolted connections, but we'll cross that bridge when we get there.

The replacement cap was designed in our spare time at work using CATIA V5, and converted to .stl files using CATIA.

Sliced using Cura. I used a 3-layer wall thickness at a 0.2 resolution, with a 40% infill. This makes the cap relatively heavy, but hopefully more durable. It would have been more ideal to have completely solid 100% fill in the area of the bolted connections, but I'm not aware of the ability to vary infill percentages.

I used a very low support percentage, something like 5-8 percent. This gave a pretty low quality surface on the inside of the print, but that's not the side anyone sees.

My prints spent about 83m of PLA filament, and took about 25 hours to print. Just to set expectations, a full set of four takes a full 1 kg spool of filament and four days.

As usual - Tinkercad :-)

And a very small bit of Meshmixer, to trim the gear (remove unneeded axle and make sure it's even).

It's a rather simple design, obviously. Basically a roof with a 1mm slit.

I've capped the tip, so it's a bit flat, though you don't really see that anymore. Also, just to make it nice, I've made a slight round indention, so the card middle is a bit more visible.

I've had to adjust the gears quite a bit - added a big axle to have some rounding where it connects with the base holder, and make it wide enough to be printable - depending on your printer, a smaller gear might be printable, but with 0.6 nozzle and 0.3 layer height, this is the least it had to be :-)

Remix it?

Apart from more/better decoration, I think the main problem with the holder is that it obscures too much of the card - unfortunately the cards themselves only have about 1MM space that isn't used for the design, so I'm not sure if there is a good way to get more visibility, apart perhaps from making a deeper indentation in the middle?

Also, if someone found a way to make it more steampunk-ish, that'd be great. All I know is how to slap on a few gears and maybe try to fake a piping, but in this case everything's so small...

description.text:
My entry in to Prestons design contest. In the pictures it has a total of 38+ pounds hanging from it with no sign of cracking, bending, flexing, or any other form of deformation. The one shown and the STL are slightly different do to redesign, but work exactly the same.

The print shown was done with Hatchbox pla. With 20% infill density.

NOTICE: The STL looks messed up in preview, That's because my software is missing an STL export plugin and I had to use an online convertor. The print still comes out fine.

UPDATE: The 38+ pounds have been hanging on it for a week now. It has been hot, humid, dry, cold, even storms (Oklahoma weather). No signs of deformation, still holding strong.

Check out Prestons channel, as well as the contest video!
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVH-GfD4Sfo

description.text:
We have been using a small plastic bowl to store bath crayons. This has a few issues. Scooping the crayons out of the water with the bowl means you have a bowl full of water, and it takes a bunch of passes to get them all. Then, if you store the bowl in the shower and do something crazy, like take a shower, it collects water. End result is a handful of colored mush.

This is designed to fix both of those problems. The bottom of the bowl is extremely porous and raised with little feet to allow water to strain through, and to let the crayons fully dry out. The lid is designed to cover the top - not necessarily to be airtight, as that would inhibit drying (and also be pointless, due to the porous bottom and difficulties with 3d printer accuracy), but to prevent water from falling from above to get into the bowl.

Printer:

Folger Tech Kossel Rev B

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 or 0.3mm

Infill:

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

When testing this I had it pop loose right near the end - just after it printed a couple layers of the feet. It's not ideal, but it did the most important parts, so I'm keeping it. This is a really good candidate for some brim to keep it firmly attached to the bed. As it is there is such a small surface that touches the build plate that even without using ABS in an air conditioned house without an enclosure you will run the risk of the box releasing itself for you before you are ready.

This was designed with a 0.4mm nozzle and the expected 0.48mm extrusion width. If you print with 3 perimeters, it will be solid - 2 outside perimeters, 2 inside perimeters, and an infil squiggle. I made it so thick because I'm pretty sure it will be impossible to prevent my children from playing with it at some point, and I wanted it to be strong enough.

With a 0.6mm nozzle it still prints fine, but you are going to have a a single perimeter inside and out with a little infill.

Print it top-side down (as aligned in the stl files - you shouldn't have to change orientation) for best printing. You don't need to print both bowls, they are just options. The short bowl is almost certainly more than enough, but the tall one is in there in case you bought the 64 bath crayon box (I'm pretty sure that's not a thing).

If you can bridge the width of the bowl, leave supports off. The occasional scraggly bridge will in fact improve the performance of this bowl. There are 3 layers of 2 wide bridge if you print at 0.2 or 2 layers at 0.3, so even if you drop a few of them, there is a chance each of them will recover anyway. Even if one does fail entirely, they are close enough together that the bowl should remain usable unless you lose both passes of two adjacent rows unless your crayons are particularly haggard.

If your bridges are that terrible that you might fail 8-12 adjacent bridges all the way though or you have a printer that just can't bridge at all for whatever reason, you could use supports, but it will make me cry a little. I won't know you are doing it or who you are, but I will be struck with melancholy when it happens anyway. If you comment and say to you want a bridge-less version, I will make one where the feet go on afterward so you can print it with the bottom flat on your bed.
If it warps off the bed (like mine did) you may need to shave down the top of the box to get it to fit inside the lid. Otherwise, it's good to go.

title: EMAX Babyhawk - Small (300mah) battery holder mount sleeve adapter thing

description.text:
The battery strap on the Babyhawk isn't small enough for the tiny batteries that many people recommend. Getting a nano-tech 300mah battery to stay in there is a pain.

So this adapter makes things a little bit easier at least!

It was a happy accident that you can even route your wires through the side holes. I made them mostly to save weight, but they work well for tucking your balance plug in there and running the JST wires in the other side.

I made this for Turnigy Nano-tech 300mah batteries. It also works with Pulse Ultra 300mah batteries, so I imagine it would work with others as well. Once you tighten the battery strap, these small batteries can slide in and out so you don't have to undo the strap every time you want to change them.

I'm sure you'll get the best fit using a flexible filament. I used Sainsmart TPU. And the battery could still come out (or partially slide out) in a crash.

title: HyperCube printable X bushing with integrated clamp

description.text:
This is Parametric Bushing by Dennis Hofmann (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2202854) with integrated handles to direct attaching to X carriage. I also added optional gap inside bushing to lower friction.

Generally i always have problem with clamped igus style bushings because they are squeezed and deforming by clamps. Furthermore double standard length bushings are not aligned and wobbling a bit. This bushing solved theese problems.

ABS is not suitable because it sticking to rods. PETG is the best.

Before print adjust theese variables in scad!

  • inner_diameter_in_millimeter
  • extrusion_width_in_millimeter
  • number_of_perimeters
  • number_of_teeth

//Edit: added bushing with 10.25mm inner and 16mm outer diameter.

Printer:

HyperCube remix

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Customize SCAD for your nozzle size, print standing top.
Refer to original bushing project for detailed instructions: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2202854

Fitting bushing onto rod
  • First remove rods from x gantry.
  • Preheat the rod with heatgun or blowtorch to such a temperature that you will not be able to touch it with a bare hand ( ~80° C for PETG, lower for PLA bushing).
  • Slide bushing onto rod. When bushing cant fit then predrill hole with 8mm drill.
  • Cool down the rod with cold water.
  • Repeat process for second bushing rod.
  • Mount rods and x carriage with attached bushings into printer (don't attach belts yet).
  • Move x carriage - if it moves freerly then job is complete.
  • But when you have to put a lot of force to slide carriage then another step is required.
  • This step is bit tricky - you need to heat up small fragment of both rods without removing them and bushings from printer (and without melting other parts of printer ;) ). After heating slide x carriage couple times until it will moves freerly, then quickly remove and cool down rods. I suggest to remember which rod is on top and which is on bottom. My rods has slightly different diameters ( because the were very cheap ).

description.text:
These are sides/fenders for a pinewood derby car. The idea was to make the proportions more like a real car, and limit the amount of wood work to make a pretty nice car.

It is regulation size. The fenders barely stick out past the wheels, and it is about 7 inches long.

I had to add about 1oz of weight to get to 5oz.

Printer:

Kossel 250

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Doesn't Matter

Infill:

Doesnt' matter

Notes:

If you're looking for a smooth finish, make at least 4-5 top layers to give enough material to sand the layer lines smooth.

1 - Cut the block to size

Once you have both sides printed, line them up on the car. You may want the wheels temporarily on the car for this. Once you have everything in place, mark the top profile to be cut with a pencil.

Cut the block to shape.

2 - Glue the sides on & finish.

I used gorilla glue on the sides. Once they are dry, sand & fill the seams until you're happy with the finish. I used elmers wood putty.

In order to get the head logos large enough to hold pennies, the whole thing ends up being a little too big for small hands to play with, which is a shame. However, it came out so nice I decided to upload anyway. Maybe I'll revise sometime to hold dimes instead of pennies to see if I can reduce the size.

I included the original idea which was a more standard spinner with embossed head logos. The idea here was to print in two colors to make the logos really stand out. That version should more easily fit smaller hands.

Printed in clear PLA. It is not nearly as fragile as it looks. Slightly modified caps

I modified the locking caps to only have a .5mm shoulder instead of 1.0mm and also added a .25mm rim. Both of these make the fit and finish look MUCH better as the air space between caps and bearing all but disapears. Finally, a fillet was added on the front side for comfort.

Fully assembled This two color version is better for small hands

Per the video, add (5) pennies to each logo in order to weight the spinner. These went in much tighter than the bearing so a rubber mallet was definitely needed. After cleaning out the bearing grease with WD-40, it spins forever!

description.text:
My solution to store my Dicemasters dice and cards.
It is modular so I can add more trays if I get more dice.

There are 3 models :

  • The dice tray, holding 35 dice.
  • The card tray currently about 4.5cm high but can easily be changed to any height required
  • The lid, to be slid into the top tray of the stack

All models have rails so they can slide into one another.
The bottoms of both the dice and card trays have are not filled so I can easily push out cards/dice out of the trays.

This first iteration is very "blocky". Next time I need to print some I will probably cut some holes/designs in the side walls and the lid.

First design inspired by https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1003238

description.text:
Since I had plans to use a bowden setup with CompRevTech's S.T.E.V.E printer I made these parts that bolts on the extruder mounting plate.
there are 4 versions:

  1. normal without a radial fan setup and no mount for a 12mm inductive sensor.
  2. normal with a mount for a 12mm inductive sensor.
  3. Radial 1 setup for usage of a radial fan and shroud from the Hypercube by Tech2c
  4. Radial 2 setup is the same as above, only difference is that it includes a 12mm holder for a inductive sensor aswell.

version 1 and 2 moves the extruder a little further out compared to the Titan Extruder setup.
Version 3 and 4 moves it even further (10mm more than the version 1 and 2) due to the ducting.
Version 1 allows for usage of the dual fan setup as designed by CompRevTech.
Version 2 is limited to only one fan of the left side due to the inductive sensor setup.

You can use the clamp that Tech2C designed: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1752766
(E3D_clamp)

Mounting hardware for Version 1 and 2:
4x M3x10mm with 4x M3 nuts
2x M3x16mm with 2x M3 nuts (for the clamp)

Mounting hardware for Version 3 and 4:
4x M3x10mm with 4x M3 nuts
2x M3x16mm with 2x M3 nuts (for the clamp)
1x M3x20mm with 1x M3 nut (nut not realy required but can be usefull) for the fan

title: Voron Redesigned Belted lead screw drive for z axis

description.text:
I very much like the belt-synced z drive mod from SIERRA086 for the excellent Voron printer. I just recreated the parts in 2 pieces each in order to make them easier to print. I removed all large overhangs. Also, my redesign resembles a bit more the look of the original Voron parts.
The motor mount can alternatively be used to house two passive idler pulleys (like the Voron a/b idler pulleys with 4 623(?) bearings). I use this in my current design as i could not get a short enough closed loop belt which can be tensioned with only the 2 lead screw mounts and the motor mount. Therefore i currently need a fourth motor mount for the passive idlers.
When mounting a motor, only the 'top' part of the motor mount is really needed.

Discussion here: https://www.reddit.com/r/voroncorexy/comments/6ccxbc/voron_redesigned_belted_lead_screw_drive_for_z/

Update 1 (May 25th 2017):

  • Added 5mm slot versions
  • Fixed alignment/orientation of parts

comments.text: Little warning about this split version. I've printed mine in PETG and had trouble getting everything tensioned and lined up. The motor mount had quite some bend as I tensioned the belt. Using ABS might be a requirement for this remix.

description.text:

Pain in the ass to screw in, as you will need a thin screwdriver, but making the sphere smaller or the base larger was something I didn't want to do.
I then proceeded to spray-paint the knob.
For best resistance, I think you should print it laying on the side, as you will be pulling it and you don't want the force to be opposed by the lamination of the object.

In meinem Fall waren sind das gerundet für
X 8000/99,40 = 80,48
Y 8000/99,38 = 80,50
